  "prompt": "\"We think your work speaks for itself, so there's no need to write a cover letter.\" Is this a test from Google interviewers? Should I write a cover letter?",
  "response": "If Google interviewers have indicated that \"your work speaks for itself\" and that there's no need for a cover letter, it likely means they have confidence in your qualifications based on your portfolio or resume. In this case, writing a cover letter may not be necessary and could even be viewed as redundant.\n\nHowever, if you feel strongly about providing a cover letter\u2014perhaps to showcase your enthusiasm for the position, explain any unique aspects of your experience, or clarify any points in your resume\u2014it's generally acceptable to include one. Just make sure it's concise and directly relevant to the role you're applying for. \n\nUltimately, it's best to follow the guidance provided by the interviewers. If they have explicitly stated that no cover letter is required, you could choose to forgo it unless you have specific reasons to include one.",
